<br>
1.  They are a support class, thus in grouping situations the group depends on them for healing, evacs, buffs, some nuking and rooting.  <br>
<br>
2.  They are a very easy class to solo with.  Solo players that spend all their time soloing are generally lacking in grouping skills.  <br>
<br>
A druid can be a great player...at soloing but be incompetent for grouping because of lack of experience.  Just imagine a player that is not used to having to heal his group and you put him on the spot where he's in charge of keeping everyone alive, sometimes they just crack.  A well played druid is a great asset for his group.  Just saying that the above two points has lead me to be in situations where I'm grouped with newbie druids when it comes to grouping.  <br>
<br>
Necros could fit into the same category because they're also a highly soloable class.  The main difference is a group doesn't depend on  necro to do its job to keep the group alive.  Necros aren't an active healer, don't group gate, or do other critical functions for a group that a druid can do.  Thus when a necro sucks he/she doesn't stick out as much as a druid.  <br>
<br>
Yeah there's shitty Warriors, Enchanters, and Clerics.  However those three are group dependent classes, thus they tend to have more experience at grouping then classes with a high level of soloability.  How many Warriors, Enchanters, and Clerics do you know that soloed their way to 50 untwinked or gimped?  Probably very very few.  I knew of TONS of druids that soloed their way to 50 that didn't know a thing about grouping, that is the basis of my rant.   <p>----------------------- <BR>
